banks in the future?

00:04:33.883 --> 00:04:34.800
AUDIENCE: I think yes.

00:04:34.800 --> 00:04:36.960
I think it's hard to
dislodge institutions

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:40.800
with that much inertia.

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:42.810
But they may not look
the way they look.

00:04:42.810 --> 00:04:46.260
They may get
slightly more agile,

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:48.750
adapt, and have
digital currency.

00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:52.710
They might pull in some
of the fintech disruptors.

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:54.430
So yes, we'll have
commercial banks,

00:04:54.430 --> 00:04:58.188
but they may not look
precisely like they do today.

00:04:58.188 --> 00:05:00.730
GARY GENSLER: I, too, think that
we'll have commercial banks.

00:05:00.730 --> 00:05:03.240
And I think it's more
than just inertia.

00:05:03.240 --> 00:05:07.530
I think that there's certain
network effects that we've

00:05:07.530 --> 00:05:11.010
seen for centuries about
bringing depositors

00:05:11.010 --> 00:05:15.760
and borrowers together and
forming that intersection, sort

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:18.730
of like a neck of an
hourglass, but forming

00:05:18.730 --> 00:05:22.930
that intersection where the
grains of sand, money and risk,

00:05:22.930 --> 00:05:27.670
flow between depositors who
have money but want to save it,

00:05:27.670 --> 00:05:29.960
and borrowers who
want to borrow it,

00:05:29.960 --> 00:05:32.380
and the commercial banks
bring that together.

00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:34.600
Peer to peer lending
has been around now

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:38.500
for some 15 years, this
concept that we don't need

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:40.840
an intermediary in the middle.

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:42.820
And then maybe
borrowers and lenders

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:46.140
can come together on
a technology platform.

00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:49.210
And it's had some success,
not just here in the US,

00:05:49.210 --> 00:05:51.970
but it started in Europe.

00:05:51.970 --> 00:05:53.290
It's been here in the US.

00:05:53.290 --> 00:05:58.390
It's been in China with great
numbers and some challenges

00:05:58.390 --> 00:05:59.600
as well.

00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:02.500
But I think what we've seen
is, by and large, we still

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:05.200
have some centralized
marketplaces that

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:07.327
come together.

00:06:07.327 --> 00:06:09.910
Now that's not the only reason
I think commercial banking will

00:06:09.910 --> 00:06:12.400
be around, but I think there
are significant network

00:06:12.400 --> 00:06:17.210
effects pulling at the center.

00:06:17.210 --> 00:06:21.400
How do you best assess the
viability of a fintech project?

00:06:21.400 --> 00:06:23.400
ROMAIN: Carlos, you like
to take a stab at that?

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:29.330
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:06:29.330 --> 00:06:33.570
So I think there's
a couple elements.

00:06:33.570 --> 00:06:39.200
One is to what degree
is it an improvement

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:42.920
relative to a
traditional product?

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:45.472
How much more convenient
is it for users?

00:06:45.472 --> 00:06:46.930
And how much more
accessible is it?

00:06:46.930 --> 00:06:49.790
I think those are
important factors.

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:51.540
Of course, there's a
financial liability.

00:06:51.540 --> 00:06:54.150
You have to look at the actual
economics of the product

00:06:54.150 --> 00:06:56.290
to see whether or not
it's scalable, above all,

00:06:56.290 --> 00:06:59.990
and whether it makes sense
to have it at a large degree.

00:06:59.990 --> 00:07:03.140
And then ultimately,
I think we've

00:07:03.140 --> 00:07:06.800
seen, especially
the last five years,

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:09.412
whether fintech
companies can actually

00:07:09.412 --> 00:07:11.870
become publicly owned companies,
how they handle themselves

00:07:11.870 --> 00:07:13.140
in the stock market, et cetera.

00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:15.473
So I think there's been several
phases to the evolution,

00:07:15.473 --> 00:07:17.040
and it's continuing.

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:20.780
GARY GENSLER: So very
helpful, in part.

00:07:20.780 --> 00:07:24.380
So first Carlos said
fundamentally, you have

00:07:24.380 --> 00:07:26.390
to have a value proposition.

00:07:26.390 --> 00:07:28.880
I'm using my words, but
sort of translating it,

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:30.380
if that's all right, Carlos.

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:32.540
So what pain points
are you addressing?

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:36.500
What gap in the current
system of finance?

00:07:36.500 --> 00:07:39.830
And it might be about user
interface and user experience.

00:07:39.830 --> 00:07:42.320
And as mobile phones
came along, as we

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:45.920
moved from online banking
and online trading

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:48.680
to mobile banking and
mobile trading that,

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:50.730
creates opportunities.

00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:53.870
Many of those opportunities
have already happened.

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:57.410
They're not all done, but
many of those opportunities

00:07:57.410 --> 00:08:01.610
of that transition from bricks
and mortar to the internet,

00:08:01.610 --> 00:08:03.510
to mobile phones, have happened.

00:08:03.510 --> 00:08:06.650
But they create opportunities
of user experience and user

00:08:06.650 --> 00:08:07.550
interface.

00:08:07.550 --> 00:08:11.450
But it has to address some
pain point, do something

00:08:11.450 --> 00:08:13.650
quicker, cheaper, better.

00:08:13.650 --> 00:08:17.630
It's an old saw in
terms of strategy.

00:08:17.630 --> 00:08:20.480
But then Carlos is
also saying we need

00:08:20.480 --> 00:08:23.990
to have financial viability.

00:08:23.990 --> 00:08:25.850
At some point in
time, you have to be

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:29.240
able to build a model where
revenues are more than costs.

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:31.910
A lot of these startups are
looking for that sweet spot,

00:08:31.910 --> 00:08:34.820
that sort of nirvana
moment when you

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:38.030
build a platform, where platform
economics and the network

00:08:38.030 --> 00:08:39.630
effects take off.

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:41.390
But Carlos said you
still have to have

00:08:41.390 --> 00:08:43.842
some financial viability
at some point in time.

00:08:43.842 --> 00:08:45.592
I think there was
another hand up, Romain.

