00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:16.940
alternative data actually going
to increase or reduce risks

00:09:16.940 --> 00:09:18.175
looking forward.

00:09:18.175 --> 00:09:19.550
GARY GENSLER: So
Michael, I think

00:09:19.550 --> 00:09:21.590
what you're saying
is you still have

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:24.470
to live within
regulatory constraints

00:09:24.470 --> 00:09:29.120
and social constraints in terms
of there's normative behavior,

00:09:29.120 --> 00:09:33.350
and this is a highly regulated
field, and for good reason.

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:35.840
We're dealing with
trust, and trust

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:37.820
is at the center of finance.

00:09:37.820 --> 00:09:40.750
We're also dealing with other
people's money and livelihood

00:09:40.750 --> 00:09:42.830
and savings and investments.

00:09:42.830 --> 00:09:44.600
And so there's
investor protection,

00:09:44.600 --> 00:09:49.220
there's consumer protection, and
in terms of alternative data,

00:09:49.220 --> 00:09:51.800
the basic tenets
around the globe

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:57.050
that when you extend credit
or offer somebody insurance,

00:09:57.050 --> 00:09:59.600
it should be done
fairly and unbiased.

00:09:59.600 --> 00:10:03.770
And so how do we ensure that
the use of alternative data

00:10:03.770 --> 00:10:08.750
still stays within those social
and legal norms about offering

00:10:08.750 --> 00:10:14.090
credit and insurance in
an unbiased and fair way.

00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:17.990
I think that's what you
were chatting about.

