00:21:20.780 --> 00:21:22.770
is your point.

00:21:22.770 --> 00:21:25.250
So we're going to
dive in a little bit.

00:21:25.250 --> 00:21:27.140
And just sort of
summarizing, I talk

00:21:27.140 --> 00:21:30.260
about the technology stack.

00:21:30.260 --> 00:21:32.300
And the cloud,
mobile, the internet

00:21:32.300 --> 00:21:36.140
were important parts that were
added to the finance technology

00:21:36.140 --> 00:21:40.250
stack, really, from the
1990s all the way till now.

00:21:40.250 --> 00:21:44.560
And if you look at
big finance, all

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:47.110
using the internet, of
course, from the late '90s,

00:21:47.110 --> 00:21:49.480
and into the naughts,
all pretty much

00:21:49.480 --> 00:21:53.530
rolling out mobile applications,
particularly in the last 10

00:21:53.530 --> 00:21:58.420
years, often because of the
pressures from startups.

00:21:58.420 --> 00:22:02.230
Not so much all have
rolled in the cloud.

00:22:02.230 --> 00:22:05.290
And many big finance
companies are still having

00:22:05.290 --> 00:22:07.810
their centralized
data structures.

00:22:07.810 --> 00:22:09.640
But more and more
are using the cloud.

00:22:09.640 --> 00:22:11.200
What's important
about the cloud,

00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:15.310
though, is that it gives
startups a real chance

00:22:15.310 --> 00:22:18.610
to sort of rent versus bill.

00:22:18.610 --> 00:22:21.580
So you don't have to build
your own data structure,

00:22:21.580 --> 00:22:26.110
put it in Microsoft Azure,
put it in an Amazon AWS,

00:22:26.110 --> 00:22:29.870
put it in [INAUDIBLE]
equivalents and so forth.

00:22:29.870 --> 00:22:32.860
So those were all earlier
technologies fully

00:22:32.860 --> 00:22:35.240
in the finance technology stack.

00:22:35.240 --> 00:22:37.840
But we've talked a lot
about in this class machine

00:22:37.840 --> 00:22:40.050
learning, natural
language processing,

00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:44.090
the critical pieces,
really, in the last call it

00:22:44.090 --> 00:22:49.330
seven to 10 years, that
computational power

00:22:49.330 --> 00:22:55.390
and the ability to analyze
data and extract correlations.

00:22:55.390 --> 00:22:59.440
And what machine learning
at its core does best,

00:22:59.440 --> 00:23:03.100
it's remarkable at extracting
correlations, pattern

00:23:03.100 --> 00:23:05.000
recognition, if you wish.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:08.440
And that pattern
recognition on data

00:23:08.440 --> 00:23:11.570
has started to really be
important in this field.

00:23:11.570 --> 00:23:13.320
And we'll talk a little
bit more about it.

00:23:13.320 --> 00:23:17.620
But it's also access to
data and digital interfaces

00:23:17.620 --> 00:23:23.010
through open application
program interfaces, or API.

00:23:23.010 --> 00:23:25.680
And you could have machine
learning and natural language

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:28.890
processing without
open API, but open API

00:23:28.890 --> 00:23:30.790
is a really important
piece of this,

00:23:30.790 --> 00:23:34.660
particularly as startups
try to get into this space.

00:23:34.660 --> 00:23:36.750
And as we talked
about, some of that's

00:23:36.750 --> 00:23:40.440
because the official sector
says, thou shall do this.

00:23:40.440 --> 00:23:44.310
Some of it is technologically
facilitated by companies

00:23:44.310 --> 00:23:46.530
that provided that access.

00:23:46.530 --> 00:23:52.050
And then many of the incumbents
wanted to provide it as well.

00:23:52.050 --> 00:23:53.940
And then, of course,
there's a whole bunch

00:23:53.940 --> 00:23:55.940
of things that have been
in the technology stack

00:23:55.940 --> 00:23:57.710
for decades or centuries.

00:23:57.710 --> 00:23:59.840
We took those as givens.

00:23:59.840 --> 00:24:02.480
And I think at some
point, when this course is

00:24:02.480 --> 00:24:05.480
taught in the 2030s,
machine learning

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:07.460
will just be taken as a given.

00:24:07.460 --> 00:24:09.320
Open API will be a
given, and there'll

00:24:09.320 --> 00:24:11.720
be new technologies beyond that.

00:24:11.720 --> 00:24:15.320
Now we talked about one
that's really in insurance.

00:24:15.320 --> 00:24:17.360
And I kid the class a
little bit because I

00:24:17.360 --> 00:24:20.840
know the interest has been more
in payments and in challenger

00:24:20.840 --> 00:24:22.810
banks and neo banks.

00:24:22.810 --> 00:24:26.540
But why I find insurance
so interesting is it's

00:24:26.540 --> 00:24:29.820
starting to layer a new
technology into the technology

00:24:29.820 --> 00:24:30.320
stack.

00:24:30.320 --> 00:24:35.150
We don't see this as much in the
challenger banks and in credit.

00:24:35.150 --> 00:24:40.210
But sensor data, telematics
in the automobiles,

00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:42.640
wearables and the like.

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:46.840
All that remarkable amount of
data to assess and underwrite

00:24:46.840 --> 00:24:49.870
insurance risk, whether
it's on an automobile,

00:24:49.870 --> 00:24:52.750
whether it's on
a home, will that

00:24:52.750 --> 00:24:56.650
come into the technology
stack of banks and credit card

00:24:56.650 --> 00:24:57.580
companies?

00:24:57.580 --> 00:25:00.630
We haven't yet seen it.

00:25:00.630 --> 00:25:05.390
But other than sort of social
norms and regulatory reasons,

00:25:05.390 --> 00:25:09.350
why wouldn't we see that wealth
of data from your automobile,

00:25:09.350 --> 00:25:14.330
from your wearables, from
Internet of Things sensors

00:25:14.330 --> 00:25:18.310
wouldn't start to
influence, and one

00:25:18.310 --> 00:25:21.910
might say infiltrate, into
how credit decisions are

00:25:21.910 --> 00:25:26.390
made, again, within the
regulatory construct

00:25:26.390 --> 00:25:27.290
and so forth.

00:25:27.290 --> 00:25:30.550
So one of the reasons why I
find insurance so fascinating,

00:25:30.550 --> 00:25:33.370
because there's sort
of another technology

00:25:33.370 --> 00:25:35.680
that they're starting
to use to collect data.

00:25:35.680 --> 00:25:37.280
Really important.

00:25:37.280 --> 00:25:39.340
And then lastly,
we've talked a lot

00:25:39.340 --> 00:25:41.050
about blockchain technology.

00:25:41.050 --> 00:25:42.830
I teach it as well.

00:25:42.830 --> 00:25:44.470
I find it a fascinating area.

00:25:44.470 --> 00:25:47.290
But just as that back
and forth with Luke,

00:25:47.290 --> 00:25:48.550
I put question marks.

00:25:48.550 --> 00:25:51.490
Will it come into that
full technology stack?

00:25:51.490 --> 00:25:53.830
It's most definitely been
a catalyst for change.

00:25:53.830 --> 00:25:57.370
It's pushing at the
edges of finance.

00:25:57.370 --> 00:26:00.880
It's starting to make each
institution, whether it's

00:26:00.880 --> 00:26:03.700
JP Morgan thinking
about a new way

00:26:03.700 --> 00:26:06.640
to do payments with
something called JP Morgan

00:26:06.640 --> 00:26:10.300
Coin, or a whole collection
of incumbent banks

00:26:10.300 --> 00:26:17.250
around a project called Finality
or utility settlement coin.

00:26:17.250 --> 00:26:20.410
We have, of course,
seen how Facebook

00:26:20.410 --> 00:26:24.130
caught a great deal of
attention in 2019 and 2020

00:26:24.130 --> 00:26:26.320
with their Facebook
Libra project,

00:26:26.320 --> 00:26:30.370
a consortium to roll out
a new global currency,

00:26:30.370 --> 00:26:33.680
both multi-basket
and single currency.

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:37.810
So incumbents in big tech are
taking very close look at this.

00:26:37.810 --> 00:26:39.700
And then you have the
Central Bank of China,

00:26:39.700 --> 00:26:42.070
People's Bank of
China doing something

00:26:42.070 --> 00:26:46.900
called a digital currency
electronic payments program.

00:26:46.900 --> 00:26:48.820
It's not using
blockchain technology.

00:26:48.820 --> 00:26:52.060
But for sure it's inspired
by cryptocurrencies.

00:26:52.060 --> 00:26:58.090
It's for sure put a higher
emphasis for all central banks

00:26:58.090 --> 00:27:00.970
around the globe to consider
what's called central bank

00:27:00.970 --> 00:27:02.660
digital currencies.

00:27:02.660 --> 00:27:05.170
So I put some question marks
because we know it's already

00:27:05.170 --> 00:27:07.960
been a catalyst for change,
but will it actually

00:27:07.960 --> 00:27:11.130
be incorporated in
the technology stack?

00:27:11.130 --> 00:27:12.850
Romain, any questions?

00:27:16.430 --> 00:27:18.270
ROMAIN: Let's wait
just another second.

00:27:18.270 --> 00:27:18.830
Yes, Hassan.

